NEWCASTLE DISEASE, POULTRY - AZERBAIJAN
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 22 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_35.HTM#Sec9>

Newcastle disease in Azerbaijan
-------------------------------
(last outbreak of Newcastle disease in Azerbaijan reported to the OIE:
October 2001).
This information was received on 18 Jan 2006 (dated 17 Jan 2006) from Dr
Ismayil Murshud Gasanov, Head, State Veterinary Service, Ministry of
Agriculture, Baku:
Reason for immediate notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report declaring the
outbreak(s) ended.
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 6 Jan 2006.
Date of start of the event: 6 Jan 2006.
Clinical disease: yes.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
1st administrative division: Masalli district
Lower administrative division: ...
Type of epidemiological unit: ...
Name of the location: village of Binakhodzhavar
Date of start of the outbreak: 6 Jan 2006
Species: avi
Number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
20 / 1 / 1 / 19 / 0
Description of affected population: backyard poultry.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: State Veterinary
Laboratory, Baku
Diagnostic tests used: virological testing
Date: 14 Jan 2006
Results: positive
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive.
Control measures undertaken:
- control of wildlife reservoirs;
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- vaccination;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s).
Vaccination in response to the outbreak:
Location: village of Binakhodzhavar, district of Masalli
Species: avi
Total number of animals vaccinated: 7000
Details of the vaccine: dry vaccine against Newcastle disease strain H
Treatment of affected animals: no.
Final report: yes.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[I can't really tell, but it appears that we are reporting an unusually
large number of Newcastle disease incidents in the general Eurasian region
affected by avian influenza, probably resulting from intensified
surveillance for poultry disease in the area. - Mod.PC]
